I talked about Maina Kariuki, Alfred Sambu, Sam Nyamweya, Nick Mwendwa. All promised a new beginning that never was. I love reading history, and I will once again flashback to the past to illustrate Hegel’s assumption made almost 200 years ago.
But first a look at, well, history.
The oldest professional football league competition in the world is the Football League that consists of 72 professional association football clubs, 69 in England and three in Wales.





The Football League was founded in 1888 and originally consisted of 12 clubs.
It is from this Football League that top clubs broke away from driven by a desire to develop further.
These clubs signed the Founder Members Agreement, establishing the basic principles for the setting up of the now famous Premier League that would have commercial independence from the Football League and the English Football Association, leaving it free to organise its own broadcast and sponsorship agreement.
And the rest, as they say, is history. Many other top leagues around the world have modelled their operations similar to the English Premier League.
Now back to our Kenyan situation. From the late 1990s to early 2000s the Kenya Football Federation-run premier league had become so chaotic, with haphazard fixtures, arbitrary decisions, illogical demotions and promotions, and general financial and management malfeasance from the federation that clubs simply got fed up.



