In 1998, when multiple title winners AFC Leopards won their last league trophy, Mumias were suspended from the competition and matches involving them awarded to their opponents. The federation later reinstated the sugar millers and cancelled the awarded matches.
KFF relegated three teams Green Berets, Mafuko Bombers and Reli and promoted Brooke Bond, KCB, Red Berets, Coastal Stars and Kisumu All Stars to increase the league from 18 teams to 20 for the 1999.
Later in the season the federation without any rational decided that the league would be reduced to 18 clubs again in 2000. However, 21 teams took part. This is how.
In March of the 1999 season, KFF decided to promote Mathare United at the expense of Red Berets. The Forces side appealed and the federation readmitted them before eventually deciding to also retain Mathare in the top league.
Several matches were abandoned without being resolved. But the saga surrounding Mumias Sugar stole the show.
The club, needing to win by seven clear goals in their final league fixture to clinch the title, thrashed Kisumu All Stars 10-0 to pip Tusker to the Kenyan championship on goal difference. Mumias and All Stars were found guilty of match mixing and suspended for one year.



