But the decision to kick out Mumias was inexplicably overturned by FKF and the sugar side participated in the 2000 season.
That season started with FKF intent on reducing the league from a 24 to 16-club affair for the 2002 competition – 11 relegated and three promoted! At some point mid-season Kimbo and Utawala were added. Eventually the federation settled on 20 teams without any plausible explanation.
Eight weeks into the new season the federation decided to readmit relegated Kisumu Telekom and Brooke Bond.
Meanwhile Re-Union, relegated from top flight football, won a case in the High Court and were readmitted. Later, Mathare United and KCB demanded the dissolution of the league organisers, KFF, after the federation awarded their contested matches to Oserian under dubious circumstances.
Things came to a head in 2003. First, reigning champions Oserian Fastac were suspended from the league for failing to honour three consecutive matches. Then Kisima Bombers withdrew due to financial constraints even as KFF continued to include them in the fixtures. Brooke Bond also withdrew over financial challenges.
But the big news of that season was seven clubs from the eight that had qualified for the KFF mini league refusing to play demanding accountability from KFF. The clubs formed a loose alliance called Group of Seven to fight for their rights.



